<paragraph id="B762CE1DD0A63C2B329F5E6D28168574" pageId="5" pageNumber="64">AZERBAIJAN. 1 ♂ (TNU), Gobustan, Beyuk-Dash, 17.05.2001, E.F. Huseynov.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="B2FE88EAE960461B42B58F74B6A6566E" pageId="5" pageNumber="64" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="708AE1AB9A9A1181BB4EFAE41EABFCED" pageId="5" pageNumber="64">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="4EE93D6E2BC9963068D72C10404B7C45" pageId="5" pageNumber="64">
Males of 
<taxonomicName id="CD52C8138CCAA54EF17CA73838F3B174" class="Arachnida" family="Gnaphosidae" genus="Haplodrassus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Haplodrassus invalidus" order="Araneae" pageId="5" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="invalidus">Haplodrassus invalidus</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished from all other 
<taxonomicName id="E2458A666899B53D7AF1DB0898930716" class="Arachnida" family="Gnaphosidae" genus="Haplodrassus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Haplodrassus" order="Araneae" pageId="5" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Haplodrassus</taxonomicName>
species by the peculiar thin embolus with an inner spur-like process, and also the peculiar shape of the RTA, which is not indented and has a claw-like tip (Figs 32-34).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="31687A489239B4CF99B5BAB58378472A" pageId="5" pageNumber="64" type="description">
<paragraph id="C56A31F7C0D662DFCEC44DA455E9A7A6" pageId="5" pageNumber="64">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="32C93B5DD012E72A18BCC1AF9E756EEB" pageId="5" pageNumber="64">
Well described by 
<bibRefCitation id="48971C80F991A98C5D7BCCF383EECCFF" author="Levy, G" journalOrPublisher="Israel Journal of Zoology" pageId="13" pageNumber="72" pagination="1 - 37" title="Spiders of the genera Drassodes and Haplodrassus (Araneae, Gnaphosidae) from Israel." volume="50" year="2004">Levy (2004)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<caption id="B42F91FEBCB1A489B12E6C3CEC23C6A6" pageId="5" pageNumber="64">
<paragraph id="3CDBA49D6975B02BBFD24B01F8444F49" pageId="5" pageNumber="64">
Figures 32-34. Males of 
<taxonomicName id="7C7786F283AE8237DE3061F1AC01EEB6" class="Arachnida" family="Gnaphosidae" genus="Haplodrassus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Haplodrassus invalidus" order="Araneae" pageId="5" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="invalidus">Haplodrassus invalidus</taxonomicName>
from Azerbaijan: 32 bulbus, apical view 33 RTA, retrolateral view 34 palp, ventral view.
</paragraph>
</caption>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="39FC681B734B60B187439917D4598FAB" pageId="5" pageNumber="64" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="CB0DA88C36E8C3B94B1A7A96831E5440" pageId="5" pageNumber="64">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="21671DF30D8963B8742B42EEB4308D1D" pageId="5" pageNumber="64">
Spain, Corsica, Italy (mainland and Sicily), Turkey, Israel and Azerbaijan (
<bibRefCitation id="6957532B4C8E70E4E81CDBE4F1653089" author="Levy, G" journalOrPublisher="Israel Journal of Zoology" pageId="13" pageNumber="72" pagination="1 - 37" title="Spiders of the genera Drassodes and Haplodrassus (Araneae, Gnaphosidae) from Israel." volume="50" year="2004">Levy 2004</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="5E15F146D6D8F11808FB8EEE0A2D6E48" pageId="5" pageNumber="64">Platnick 2012</bibRefCitation>
; present data).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="B91DBEAFEA2780FD9BEF7C3F33E43D52" pageId="5" pageNumber="64" type="comments">
<paragraph id="6176E15737A2F587FA5C236427DC005C" pageId="5" pageNumber="64">Comments.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="3FF250FA7CA09ACD12798A7114189E32" pageId="5" pageNumber="64">
<taxonomicName id="DD5DA68010990D2CFC5BD0C373BDAAEC" class="Arachnida" family="Gnaphosidae" genus="Haplodrassus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Haplodrassus invalidus" order="Araneae" pageId="5" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="invalidus">Haplodrassus invalidus</taxonomicName>
is a new species record for the fauna of Azerbaijan, Caucasus and the former Soviet Union. Azerbaijan is the easternmost point of the known distribution range.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
